    <name>
      <text>Rewrite a complex exponential relationship into logarithmic form</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>During a simulation, a machine amplifies a signal using exponential growth. After several cycles, the signal reaches a strength of \({@number@}\), 
generated using base \({@base@}\).</p>
<p>Write the logarithmic form of the statement:</p>

<p>\[
{@base@}^{@chosen_exp@} = {@number@}
\]</p>

<p>Express your answer in the form \(\log_{a}(b)\).</p>

<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>The exponential relationship is:</p>

<p>\[
{@base@}^{@chosen_exp@} = {@number@}.
\]</p>

<p>We use the identity:</p>

<p>\[
a^k = N \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \log_a(N) = k.
\]</p>

<p>So:</p>

<p>\[
\log_{ {@base@} }({@number@}) = {@chosen_exp@}.
\]</p>

<p>This is written as:</p>

<p>\[
\frac{\log({@number@})}{\log({@base@})}.
\]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
